explanation:
Verdict: the report is correct that this use violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13. In OS_ModuleSymbolLookup the local variable record is declared as
    OS_common_record_t *record;
but it is only read (record->name_entry is passed to OS_SymbolLookup_Static) and never used to modify the referenced object. According to Rule 8.13 a pointer that is only used to access data should be qualified as pointing to const, e.g.:
    const OS_common_record_t *record;
The macro OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET expands to &tbl[index] and yields a non-const pointer type, but that does not prevent assigning the result to a pointer to const — converting from T * to const T * is allowed. Thus the macro does not "force" the pointer to be non-const; the code author chose a non-const declaration, which is the MISRA violation. If there is no intent to modify the record through this pointer, change the declaration to a pointer to const to satisfy Rule 8.13. If the record may be modified later in this function, then the non-const declaration would be required and there would be no violation, but in the shown code it is clearly only read, so the report is correct.
